ol.li:
Note that A^T A= V \Sigma^T U^T U \Sigma V^T = V \Sigma^2 V^T, so the diagonal entries of \Sigma are simply the positive roots of the eigenvalues of
    					A^T A=\mat{0 4; -1 0}\mat{0 -1; 4 0}=\mat{16 0; 0 1}
    					i.e. \sigma_1 =4, \sigma_2=1. Since A^T A is already diagonal, V is the identity matrix. The columns of U should satisfy Au_1=\sigma_1 v_1, Au_2 = \sigma_2 v_2 : by inspection one obtains
    					u_1 = \vec{0 1}, u_2=\vec{-1 0}, U = \mat{0 -1;1 0}
